    </input>

    <input name="reference_numbers" optional="true">
      <b>Reference Numbers (Optional):</b> <div whiteSpace="pre">{{ reference_numbers }}</div>
      <p><i>Case numbers, project IDs, invoice numbers, Aktenzeichen. Example: "Az.: 2025/123-M" or "Project: PRJ-2025-089"</i></p>
    </input>

    <input name="cc_recipients" optional="true">
      <b>CC Recipients (Optional):</b> <div whiteSpace="pre">{{ cc_recipients:-none }}</div>
      <p><i>Others who should receive copy. Include name and reason. Example: "Sarah Chen (project manager for visibility)"</i></p>
    </input>
  </cp>

  <cp caption="VALIDATION FRAMEWORK">
    <p><b>Pre-Send Checklist (All Must Pass):</b></p>
    <list listStyle="decimal">
      <item>
        <b>Spell Check</b>
        <list listStyle="dash">
          <item>All words spelled correctly</item>
          <item>German umlauts correct (ae/oe/ue or ä/ö/ü)</item>
          <item>Names and proper nouns verified</item>
          <item>No autocorrect errors</item>
        </list>
      </item>

      <item>
        <b>Grammar Check</b>
        <list listStyle="dash">
          <item>German: Case agreements correct (der/die/das, accusative/dative)</item>
          <item>German: Verb conjugations match subjects</item>
          <item>English: Subject-verb agreement</item>
          <item>Sentence structure clear and complete</item>
        </list>
      </item>

      <item>
        <b>Clarity Check</b>
        <list listStyle="dash">
          <item>Purpose stated clearly in first paragraph</item>
          <item>Questions are specific and answerable</item>
          <item>Action requests are unambiguous</item>
          <item>No room for misinterpretation</item>
        </list>
      </item>

      <item>
        <b>Context Check</b>
        <list listStyle="dash">
          <item>Relevant names and details included</item>
          <item>Reference numbers mentioned where applicable</item>
          <item>Previous correspondence referenced appropriately</item>
          <item>Recipient has sufficient background to understand</item>
        </list>
      </item>

      <item>
        <b>Timeline Check</b>
        <list listStyle="dash">
          <item>Deadlines stated with specific dates</item>
          <item>Dependencies mentioned if relevant</item>
          <item>Next steps clearly defined</item>
          <item>Expected response timeframe communicated</item>
        </list>
      </item>
    </list>

    <p><b>Quality Standards (Should Pass):</b></p>
    <list listStyle="dash">
      <item><b>Conciseness:</b> No unnecessary words, paragraphs, or repetition</item>
      <item><b>Scannability:</b> Key points visible without reading every word</item>
      <item><b>Tone consistency:</b> Appropriate throughout, no jarring shifts</item>
      <item><b>Professional formatting:</b> Proper spacing, logical structure</item>
      <item><b>Actionability:</b> Recipient knows exactly what to do next</item>
      <item><b>Relationship appropriate:</b> Tone matches relationship stage</item>
    </list>

    <p><b>Final Review Questions:</b></p>
    <list listStyle="dash">
      <item>Would I understand this email if I received it?</item>
      <item>Can the recipient respond in under 2 minutes if the request is simple?</item>
      <item>Does this email strengthen or at least maintain the relationship?</item>
      <item>Is everything I promised to include actually present?</item>
    </list>
  </cp>

  <cp caption="BEST PRACTICES AND GUIDELINES">
    <p><b>DO - Recommended Practices:</b></p>
    <list listStyle="dash">
      <item><b>Lead with the point:</b> State purpose in first 1-2 sentences (BLUF principle)</item>
      <item><b>One email, one topic:</b> Separate emails for separate topics improve response rates</item>
      <item><b>Use bullet points:</b> For multiple items, questions, or action items</item>
      <item><b>Be specific with deadlines:</b> "Tuesday, December 10" not "early next week"</item>
      <item><b>Make it easy to respond:</b> Yes/No questions, numbered options, clear asks</item>
      <item><b>Reference context:</b> "Following our call yesterday..." helps recipient context-switch</item>
      <item><b>Match their energy:</b> If they write formally, respond formally; if casual, match</item>
      <item><b>Proofread German carefully:</b> Umlauts, compound words, formal Sie forms</item>
      <item><b>Include your availability:</b> For meeting requests, offer specific times</item>
    </list>

    <p><b>DON'T - Common Pitfalls:</b></p>
    <list listStyle="dash">
      <item><b>Don't bury the ask:</b> Key request should not be in paragraph four</item>
      <item><b>Don't use vague timelines:</b> "Soon", "ASAP", "when you can" are unclear</item>
      <item><b>Don't over-apologize:</b> One apology is sufficient; repeated apologies weaken message</item>
      <item><b>Don't assume context:</b> Recipient may not remember details you do</item>
      <item><b>Don't use "per my last email":</b> Comes across as passive-aggressive</item>
      <item><b>Don't write walls of text:</b> Break into paragraphs, use whitespace</item>
      <item><b>Don't CC unnecessarily:</b> Only include people who truly need visibility</item>
      <item><b>Don't mix languages:</b> Choose one language and stick with it (technical terms excepted)</item>
      <item><b>Don't send angry:</b> Draft heated emails, wait, then revise before sending</item>
    </list>

    <p><b>German-Specific Guidelines:</b></p>
    <list listStyle="dash">
      <item><b>Always use Sie:</b> Unless explicitly on Du terms with recipient</item>
      <item><b>Titles matter:</b> Dr., Prof., Dipl.-Ing. should be used in salutation</item>
      <item><b>Compound words:</b> German creates compounds - ensure correct formation</item>
      <item><b>Formal closings:</b> "Mit freundlichen Gruessen" is standard professional</item>
      <item><b>Date format:</b> DD.MM.YYYY in German context (15.12.2025)</item>
      <item><b>Legal formality:</b> "Sehr geehrte/r" required for legal/official correspondence</item>
    </list>
  </cp>

  <cp caption="EXAMPLES - COMPLETE EMAIL COMPOSITIONS">
    <p><b>Example 1: Follow-Up Request (English)</b></p>

    <p><b>Input:</b></p>
    <list listStyle="dash">
      <item>Purpose: Follow up on contract review request sent last week</item>
      <item>Recipient: Sarah Chen, Legal Counsel at TechCorp, ongoing business relationship</item>
      <item>Language: English</item>
      <item>Tone: Professional</item>
      <item>Deadline: Need response by December 12</item>
      <item>Context: Sent contract for review on December 2, no response yet</item>
    </list>

    <p><b>Generated Email:</b></p>
    <div whiteSpace="pre">
Subject: Follow-up: Contract Review - Response Needed by Dec 12

Dear Sarah,

I wanted to follow up on the partnership agreement I sent on December 2 for your review.

I understand you have a full workload, but we're targeting contract execution by December 20 to align with our Q4 timeline. To meet this, I'd need your feedback or approval by December 12.

Key items requiring your input:
- Section 4.2: Liability caps
- Section 7.1: Termination notice period
- Exhibit A: Service level definitions

Please let me know if you need any additional information or if a brief call would help expedite the review.

Best regards,
[Your Name]
    </div>

    <p><b>Analysis:</b></p>
    <list listStyle="dash">
      <item>Subject line: Clear follow-up indicator with deadline</item>
      <item>Opening: Direct reference to original email with date</item>
      <item>Tone: Understanding but clear about deadline</item>
      <item>Action items: Specific sections needing attention</item>
      <item>Close: Offer to help, easy response path</item>
